28":"1328","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England"},"en":{"1320–1380":"1320–1380","1345–1387":"1345–1387","1364–1418":"1364–1418","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","1320":"1320","1364":"1364","1330":"1330","about 1364":"about 1364","1380":"1380","1418":"1418","1328":"1328","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tilley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Tilly-sur-Seulles (Calvados) or Tilly (Eure), France.","English: habitational name from Tyley in Wotton under Edge (Gloucestershire), Tiley in Minterne Magna (Dorset), or Tilley (Shropshire). The Gloucestershire and Dorset placenames derive from Old English <i>tigel</i> ‘tile’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The Shropshire placename derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>lēah</i>.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>tilie</i> ‘one who tills the land, a husbandman’. Compare   Tiller  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tillie","meanings":["English (northern England and southern Scotland): variant of   Tilley  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Tiller","meanings":["English (southern, especially Hampshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>tiliere</i>, <i>tilyer</i> ‘one who tills the soil, husbandman, farmer, farm laborer’. This is a derivative of Old English <i>tilian</i> ‘to till (the soil)’, Middle English <i>tilie</i>. There has been some confusion of this name with   Tyler  .","German: variant of <b>Tüller</b> (see   Tuller  )."]},{"name":"Tiley","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire, Somerset and Wiltshire): variant of   Tilley  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Tilley was born in 1320, in Glassenbury, Kent, England. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Danvers. He died in 1380, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1320–1380":"1320–1380","1345–1387":"1345–1387","1364–1418":"1364–1418","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","1320":"1320","1364":"1364","1330":"1330","about 1364":"umbes 1364","1380":"1380","1418":"1418","1328":"1328","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1320–1380":"1320–1380","1345–1387":"1345–1387","1364–1418":"1364–1418","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1453":"1453","1387":"1387","1320":"1320","1364":"1364","1330":"1330","about 1364":"noin 1364","1380":"1380","1418":"1418","1328":"1328","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England"},"fr":{"132